## Phase 1 — vitest red-state capture (RED)

Goal: prove the AC-228-01..AC-228-11 surface (Indexes tab editor body
+ chained execute + PK dedup + multi-statement preview) before
modifying `CreateTableDialog.tsx`.

Initial run after appending the Sprint 228 describe block on top of
the Sprint 227 modal (Indexes-tab body still says
`"Available in Sprint 228"`):

    pnpm vitest run src/components/schema/CreateTableDialog.test.tsx

    Test Files  1 failed (1)
    Tests  13 failed | 25 passed (38)

The 25 passing cases are the Sprint 226 + Sprint 227 carry-overs —
they are still green because the test mock surface for `@lib/tauri`
was extended to expose `createIndex` / `dropIndex` mocks but the
existing test bodies never reach those mocks.

The 13 failing cases were the new Sprint 228 cases, each with the
canonical failure mode:

  Sprint 228 — Indexes tab functional
    × Indexes tab no longer renders the 'Available in Sprint 228' placeholder (AC-228-01)
        AssertionError: expected 'Available in Sprint 228' not to contain 'Available in Sprint 228'
    × Indexes tab default state has zero index rows (AC-228-02)
    × '+ Index' adds an index row; '−' removes it (AC-228-02)
        TestingLibraryElementError: Unable to find an accessible element
        with the role "button" and name `/Add index/i`
    × index type `<Select>` exposes exactly btree | hash | gin | gist (AC-228-03)
    × renaming a column on the Columns tab updates the index columns checkbox label live (AC-228-03)
    × Show DDL fans out createTable(preview) + createIndex(preview) per declared row (AC-228-04)
    × Execute chains createTable + createIndex × 2 sequentially with one history entry (AC-228-05)
    × first createIndex(commit) rejection halts chain, modal stays open, error names failing index (AC-228-06)
    × mid-chain rejection leaves earlier index applied (no dropIndex rollback) (AC-228-07)
    × PK exact match dedup — no createIndex emitted for the row (AC-228-08)
    × PK partial overlap still emits a CREATE INDEX (AC-228-08)
    × multi-column index forwards columns array in declared order (AC-228-04 / -05)
    × unique checkbox flips is_unique on the createIndex payload (AC-228-03 / -05)
    × Safe Mode warn-cancel surfaces the canonical message even with index rows declared (AC-228-11)

All failures rooted in either:
  - The Sprint 227 placeholder body still rendering `"Available in
    Sprint 228"` instead of an editor.
  - The new aria-labelled inputs (`Index name`, `Index type`,
    `Index unique`, `Index column: <col>`, `Add index`,
    `Remove index`) not yet existing.
  - `tauri.createIndex` not yet wired in the dialog source.

## Phase 2 — implementation (GREEN)

Implementation changes (Sprint 228):

1. Replaced the Indexes-tab placeholder body with an interactive
   editor — modal-local `IndexDraft[]` state, `+ Index` / `−` row
   buttons, per-row name input + columns multi-checkbox + index type
   `<Select>` (btree/hash/gin/gist) + unique checkbox + PK-dedup
   inline note ("primary key is already indexed").
2. Wired the chained Execute closure inside the existing
   `useDdlPreviewExecution.loadPreview` `prepareCommit` factory:
   `createTable({preview_only:false})` then sequentially
   `for (const idx of declaredIndexesAfterPkDedup) await createIndex(...)`.
   Per-iteration `try/catch` re-throws as
   `Index "<name>" failed: <pg error>` so the hook's error surface
   includes the failing row's name verbatim.
3. The Show DDL preview path also fans out
   `tauri.createIndex({preview_only:true})` per declared (non-PK-dedup)
   row, and joins all `result.sql` strings with `;\n` so the inline
   preview pane shows CREATE TABLE + COMMENT ON × N + CREATE INDEX × M.
4. PK auto-emission deduplication: when a row's `columns` (in declared
   order) exactly matches the declared PK array, the row's preview-only
   AND commit-only `tauri.createIndex` calls are skipped. The row's
   inline note explains why.
5. Added 2 new Rust unit fixtures
   (`create_index_preview_gin_byte_equivalent`,
   `create_index_preview_gist_byte_equivalent`) to lock the byte-string
   for the two UI-exposed types that previously only existed inside
   the all-types-acceptance loop without a strict byte-string
   assertion. Existing 8 fixtures unchanged.

